Introduction to Map in Java

Map is an interface in Java used to store data in key-value pairs.

👉 Each element consists of:

a key (unique)
a value
How Map works
Key → Value

"apple"  → 10  
"banana" → 20

👉 You use the key to get the value.

Important Features
keys are unique
values can be duplicated
each key maps to exactly one value
not part of Collection interface (but part of Collection Framework)
Common Map Implementations
HashMap
most commonly used
fast (O(1) average)
no order
LinkedHashMap
maintains insertion order
TreeMap
sorted by keys
slower (O(log n))
Creating a Map
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
Basic Methods
put()
map.put("Apple", 10);
map.put("Banana", 20);

👉 adds or updates value

get()
map.get("Apple"); // 10
remove()
map.remove("Banana");
containsKey() / containsValue()
map.containsKey("Apple");
map.containsValue(10);
size()
map.size();
isEmpty()
map.isEmpty();
Iterating over Map
Using keySet()
for (String key : map.keySet()) {
    System.out.println(key + " " + map.get(key));
}
Using entrySet() (better)
for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
    System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " " + entry.getValue());
}
Summary
Map stores data as key → value
keys must be unique
main methods:
put() → add/update
get() → retrieve
remove() → delete
most used implementation → HashMap

